State tax systems contributed to wealth concentration, as wealthy individuals and corporations used their power to shape state tax policies to their own benefit.
The opposite is generally true for state income taxes but, in most states, total state taxes ask the most of taxpayers who can least afford it.
State taxes on inherited wealth apply only to the wealthiest individuals and are the main state taxes on wealth.
Policymakers have weakened federal and state estate taxes in recent years and, now, the federal tax reaches fewer than 1 in 1,000 estates and state estate taxes are increasingly rare.
Unlike the federal government, most states tax income from investments and income from work at the same rate.